photo.description: In the middle foreground is the top of the Bank of America tower; behind it to the left is the squat, round, glass Roy Thompson Hall opera house. Up a bit from the Opera House is the Hilton, then back from that a bit is the Sheraton, and facing the Sheraton is the New City Hall towers. The tall white one to the right is First Canadian Place, and the red one at the right edge is Scotia Plaza. I've not bothered to look up what most of the ones in the cluster in the middle are. By all means feel free to cross-check a <a href"http:maps.google.commaps?fq&amp;hlen&amp;geocode&amp;qcn+tower&amp;ieUTF8&amp;ll43.64519,-79.384267&amp;spn0.012267,0.016887&amp;th&amp;z16">satellite map<a> to get a fuller sense of the view here. In any case, even in spite of the smog, I think the view here goes out for several miles to the north-northwest. On a clear day I bet you can see all the way to the North Pole from here. I bet you can.

photo.description: Ganz umrunden können wir die in 346 Metern Höhe gelegene Aussichtsplattform des <a href"http:en.wikipedia.orgwikiCn_tower" target"_new" rel"nofollow">CN-Towers<a> nicht, denn sie beherbergt auch noch ein Restaurant. Den 360-Grad-Rundblick hat man von hier aus jedoch nicht. Den 360°-Rundblick bekommen wir erst im sogenannten Skypod, einer weiteren Plattform in 447 Metern Höhe. All diese Daten können wir dieser Tafel entnehmen, an der wir vorbeikommen, während wir in der Warteschlage vor dem Zugang zum Skypod stehen. An klaren Tagen soll man vom Skypod des <a href"http:en.wikipedia.orgwikiCn_tower" target"_new" rel"nofollow">CN-Towers<a> aus bis hinüber zu den <a href"http:en.wikipedia.orgwikiNiagara_Falls" target"_new" rel"nofollow">Niagara-Fällen<a> auf der gegenüberliegenden Seite des <a href"http:en.wikipedia.orgwikiLake_Ontario" target"_new" rel"nofollow">Ontariosees<a> sehen können, immerhin eine Entfernung von über hundert Kilometern.

photo.description: <b>Sunday March 5, 2006 4:34am<b> | <a href"http:www.flickr.comphotossmaku109055542">4:36am<a> On my way home from a friend's birthday party, I decided it was too late to go home, sleep, wake up and drive downtown again for the next morning. I made the executive decision to drive around the empty streets of Toronto and take pictures in the night. Despite the -17 celsius weather, I still ventured out as my photographer's itch got the better of me. These impromptu shoots are always fun. I always have my tripod and camera gear wherever I go so this made things a lot easier in making my decision. First stop: the intersection of Bathurst St. and Fort York Blvd. Facing East off the bridge, the picture above shows the construction going on at Cityplace, the multi-condominium complex. It was such a clear night that you can even see the stars in these photos. For the next few days, I'll be posting a new picture from this series. <a href"http:static.flickr.com50108586683_91a031f2e5_o.jpg">Best seen in its original size<a>! <b>Camera:<b> Nikon D200 <b>Lens:<b> Nikkor 24mm f2.8 D <b>Shutter Speed:<b> 20 sec. <b>F-Stop:<b> f7.1 <b>Sensitivity:<b> ISO 400
